<div id="review_2648779606" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2648779606" />
    <a title="Zac Johnson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/431978-zac-johnson"><img alt="Zac Johnson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468886470p2/431978.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2648779606?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zac Johnson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zac Johnson" href="/user/show/431978-zac-johnson">Zac Johnson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2648779606" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9000184547547065449">Hubert Selby Jr. is responsible for one of my favorite novels, the soul-shaking Requiem for a Dream. There are some glimmers of that brilliance contained in this short story collection, such as the titular tale, but there are far more misfires that only half work than there are masterpieces. Every character, for instance, is named Harry. Is this the same Harry in each story? Is it the Harry from his novels? Is Selby just really lazy when it comes to naming things? Who knows. <br/><br/>What I do know is th</span>
  <span id="freeText9000184547547065449" style="display:none">Hubert Selby Jr. is responsible for one of my favorite novels, the soul-shaking Requiem for a Dream. There are some glimmers of that brilliance contained in this short story collection, such as the titular tale, but there are far more misfires that only half work than there are masterpieces. Every character, for instance, is named Harry. Is this the same Harry in each story? Is it the Harry from his novels? Is Selby just really lazy when it comes to naming things? Who knows. <br /><br />What I do know is the collection is still worthwhile for:<br />Song of the Silent Snow: an absolute masterpiece that deserves to be regarded among the best short stories of all time<br />Fortune Cookie: Also turned into a movie by the same director, Darren Aronofsky, as Requiem for a Dream.<br />And, showing promise even if they don't have the same force we expect from the author:<br />Liebesnacht and Double Feature.<br /><br />The rest, at the very least, didn't move me. But Selby set a high bar for himself, and not everything a genius writes is going to be genius itself.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9000184547547065449" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


