<div id="review_3544663001" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3544663001" />
    <a title="Jackson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/145196-jackson"><img alt="Jackson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1227825849p2/145196.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3544663001?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jackson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jackson" href="/user/show/145196-jackson">Jackson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3544663001" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11447100438334943705">I began reading this book in July 2008. I got approximately a third of the way through it, maybe a bit more. The thing I remember most about it was taking it in my backpack for an overnight trip in Glacier National Park to Lincoln Lake, a somewhat obscure destination, at least by GNP standards. It was about seven or eight miles through thick forest to the campsite from the pull-off on the Going-to-the-Sun Road on the west side of the park. The hike took a long time, the day was foggy, the trail </span>
  <span id="freeText11447100438334943705" style="display:none">I began reading this book in July 2008. I got approximately a third of the way through it, maybe a bit more. The thing I remember most about it was taking it in my backpack for an overnight trip in Glacier National Park to Lincoln Lake, a somewhat obscure destination, at least by GNP standards. It was about seven or eight miles through thick forest to the campsite from the pull-off on the Going-to-the-Sun Road on the west side of the park. The hike took a long time, the day was foggy, the trail was wet, and visibility was bad due to tall underbrush that grew up to my face. The whole time I was very nervous about encountering a bear.<br /><br />The campground is beautiful, and I was the only one there. But the tent area sat tucked into tall underbrush and weeds, eliminating the view a bear would have of me (or I would have of it) until it was right upon me. And a tall waterfall cascaded into the lake (dropping down from Avalanche Lake), and though it was across the lake from me, the sound was loud and incessant. I couldn't see far, and I couldn't hear anything, and I was alone in bear country. Not something I was unaccustomed to, or generally fearful of, but being alone and stationary for about 18 hours in this place was a little unsettling. (And the next morning, after a drizzling overnight rain, the mud around the lake and on the trail was riddled with fresh bear pawprints.)<br /><br />After dinner, I set up my tent, lit a candle, and read a chunk of this book. Selby is probably not the best author to read while you are feeling unsettled, but for Selby, this book is mild. In fact, compared to masterpieces like <em>Requiem For a Dream</em> and <em>Last Exit to Brooklyn</em>, it is downright tame. I put it down when I returned to my apartment in Columbia Falls and never picked it up again.<br /><br />That is, until recently. Twelve-plus years later I have a daughter and am far away from Montana. I was picking up around her dollhouse, which sits in front of the bottom shelf of one of my bookcases, and found this poking out, covered in dust, with the bookmark still stuck where I left off in the woods a long time ago. So I thought, <em>What the hell</em>, and determined to finish it.<br /><br />It was a slog. A number of pieces here are meditations on the dreary, soul-draining nature of working nine-to-five and the numbing routine that comes along with it. But, for the most part, it fails to hit hard. My favorite pieces are the very short essay "Of Whales and Dreams" and the story "The Coat," about a homeless man and his coat, the only item on earth, animate or inanimate, that brings him any security or comfort. <br /><br />But that's about it. Otherwise, this is a book that misses its mark. If Selby hadn't already published masterpieces prior to this book, I doubt it would have seen the light of day. Without his name attached to it, it fails to stand on its own, and is only recommended for those who wish to read every word he ever wrote.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11447100438334943705" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

