    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1563155813" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1563155813" />
    <a title="Sarah Tipper" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17905900-sarah-tipper"><img alt="Sarah Tipper" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1634741383p2/17905900.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1563155813?book_show_action=true">Feb 28, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah Tipper" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah Tipper" href="/user/show/17905900-sarah-tipper">Sarah Tipper</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1563155813" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10328638713009556218">For the first couple of stories I found the punctuation distracting but then I stopped noticing. The depth of Selby’s characters is wonderful, you feel you’re right behind their eyes, on the inside looking out. Some of his characters are the sort of people who don’t usually get a voice. Selby covers depression, homelessness, frustrated fathers and many more characters in the fifteen short stories in this book. Sometimes you’re surprised at the places people find joy. It reminded me a little of A</span>
  <span id="freeText10328638713009556218" style="display:none">For the first couple of stories I found the punctuation distracting but then I stopped noticing. The depth of Selby’s characters is wonderful, you feel you’re right behind their eyes, on the inside looking out. Some of his characters are the sort of people who don’t usually get a voice. Selby covers depression, homelessness, frustrated fathers and many more characters in the fifteen short stories in this book. Sometimes you’re surprised at the places people find joy. It reminded me a little of A Streetcar Named Desire, Selby’s men leap from the page full of energy (which is sometimes destructive energy) like Stanley Kowalski does. I love the positive ending of the story Song Of The Silent Snow. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10328638713009556218" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


